Management of ME fisheries should be based on the best available data & science, but that clearly hasn't happened here. On behalf of Maine's lobstermen, I urge NOAA Fisheries to postpone its rulemaking and engage with stakeholders to develop an accurate risk assessment tool. 6/

And the underlying data used in the risk assessment tool might not tell us the whole picture. Stakeholders tell us there‚Äôs a good chance the model generated by the tool won‚Äôt account for the present-day distributional shift of the right whales. 5/

NOAA‚Äôs risk assessment tool is a scientific model with implications for thousands of Mainers and an entire species of whale, but it hasn‚Äôt been peer-reviewed. The tool wasn‚Äôt even made public until a few days ago. 4/

In the last 2 yrs, 12 of the 20 stranded right whales found were discovered in Canadian waters, where Canadian fishermen aren‚Äôt subject to the same whale protection measures. But the risk assessment tool fails to incorporate the impact of Canadian fisheries on whale deaths. 3/

NOAA Fisheries' new restrictions are supposed to protect the right whale. But the method NOAA uses to justify these rules ‚Äì called the ‚Äòrisk assessment tool‚Äô‚Äì uses data & assumptions that may be unreliable.

More info here:  https://golden.house.gov/media/press-releases/golden-asks-noaa-fisheries-postpone-new-right-whale-management-proposals¬†‚Ä¶
